This course seeks to provide Candidates with an appreciation of managing organizations in the international and cross-cultural context. Three key levels of analysis are explored, namely societal/cultural/country (Macro) level, organizational (Meso) level and group/individual managerial (Micro) level. Four Key questions which underlie the Course give expression to these different levels of analysis:
1. What is international management and what complexities arise when operating at the international level?
2. How do we operationalize and understand differences between countries when managing internationally and what are the implications of these differences?
3. What is the most appropriate way for firms to internationalize and to manage and structure their activities?
4. How can we develop the managerial talents and capabilities to ensure that managers can be a success internationally?
In order to address these questions, we will:
? Provide candidates with an historical overview of traditions and transitions in management thinking;
? Explore the different trajectories of International Management Research;
? Introduce candidates to key international managerial issues, the globalization thesis and contemporary environmental factors affecting organizations;
? Enable candidates to explore issues relating to the management of organizations at an international level, focusing on cultural, institutional and socio-political determinants of legitimate practice;
? Identify ethno perspectives and provide frameworks for understanding and managing in this international context.
